    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-11-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-11-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="225"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d225">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 406/99–101.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Consul-General <persName type="to">Denby</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-11-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 23, 1907</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 33.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                    dispatch No. 37, of the 7th ultimo, transmitting copies of correspondence had
                    with the legation at Peking relative to the proclamation with regard to the
                    infringement of trade-marks published by the taotai of Shanghai.</p>
                <p>By reference to the department’s instruction No. 29, of the 30th ultimo, you will
                    observe that the department has shared the impression made upon the
                    legation.</p>
                <p>I am, etc. (for the Secretary of State),</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Carr</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Chief Clerk.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
